@user27182 Thanks for the confirmation! I looked into the historical context of the `.name` check.

It appears to have been introduced in [this commit](https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/commit/7f31567f8f125bb51ae7a3097c8bc24fef6f4d58) from 2013 by @jreback as part of a broader set of fixes (GH4204, GH4463) related to Series/indexing and type coercion — notably when `Series` still subclassed `ndarray`.

Back then, checking for `.name` may have been a lightweight proxy to identify Series-like objects without introducing tight coupling, but now that we have proper ABCs (`ABCSeries`, `ABCIndexClass`), it seems more robust to explicitly check types via `isinstance`.

So unless there's some subtle compatibility case that still requires relying on `.name`, I’d proceed with:

```python
elif isinstance(data, (ABCSeries, ABCIndexClass)):
